## Coding Standards

### General Principles
- Readability over cleverness
- DRY (Don't Repeat Yourself)
- KISS (Keep It Simple)
- YAGNI (You Aren't Gonna Need It)

### Naming Conventions
| Element | Convention | Example |
|---------|------------|---------|
| Variables | camelCase | `userName`, `isActive` |
| Functions | camelCase | `getUserById`, `calculateTotal` |
| Classes | PascalCase | `UserService`, `OrderProcessor` |
| Constants | UPPER_SNAKE_CASE | `MAX_RETRY_COUNT` |
| Files (components) | PascalCase | `UserProfile.tsx` |
| Files (utilities) | kebab-case | `date-utils.ts` |

### Code Quality
- Functions < 50 lines
- 80%+ test coverage target
- TypeScript strict mode
- Document all public APIs

## Testing Requirements
- Unit tests: `[filename].test.ts`
- Integration tests: `[filename].integration.test.ts`
- Use AAA pattern (Arrange, Act, Assert)
- Cover happy path, edge cases, and error scenarios

## File Structure
- Specs: `RLM/specs/features/FTR-XXX/`
- Tasks: `RLM/tasks/active/TASK-XXX.md`
- Architecture: `RLM/specs/architecture/`

## Git Workflow
- Branch: `feature/TASK-XXX-brief-description`
- Commits: Conventional commits (`feat`, `fix`, `docs`, etc.)
- Always link to task ID in commit/PR
